\subsection{AgentTools.GenericModelAgent.AreaWiseParamGenerator module}
\label{\detokenize{AgentTools.GenericModelAgent:module-AgentTools.GenericModelAgent.AreaWiseParamGenerator}}\label{\detokenize{AgentTools.GenericModelAgent:agenttools-genericmodelagent-areawiseparamgenerator-module}}\index{AgentTools.GenericModelAgent.AreaWiseParamGenerator (module)@\spxentry{AgentTools.GenericModelAgent.AreaWiseParamGenerator}\spxextra{module}}\index{AreaWiseParamGenerator (class in AgentTools.GenericModelAgent.AreaWiseParamGenerator)@\spxentry{AreaWiseParamGenerator}\spxextra{class in AgentTools.GenericModelAgent.AreaWiseParamGenerator}}

\begin{fulllineitems}
\phantomsection\label{\detokenize{AgentTools.GenericModelAgent:AgentTools.GenericModelAgent.AreaWiseParamGenerator.AreaWiseParamGenerator}}\pysiglinewithargsret{\sphinxbfcode{\sphinxupquote{class }}\sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{AgentTools.GenericModelAgent.AreaWiseParamGenerator.}}\sphinxbfcode{\sphinxupquote{AreaWiseParamGenerator}}}{\emph{*args}, \emph{**kwargs}}{}
AreaWiseParamGenerator Organizes the parameter files required for the execution of the model. 
The user is responsible for the contents and format of the files provided.
This module only receives the files as parameters and places them in a file with a name set by the user.
By default, this module places the parameter files in a folder named ‘Parameters’.
\begin{quote}\begin{description}
\item[{Input Ports}] \leavevmode\begin{itemize}
\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{WD\_Path:} This is the working folder provided by the MainGenerator module.

\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{Parameter\_Folder\_Name:} Name of the parameter folder that will be created. The default value is Parameter.

\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{File\_In\_x :} Path of the x-th parameter file, (x=00,01,02,…15).

\end{itemize}

\item[{Output Ports}] \leavevmode\begin{itemize}
\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{Ready:} Starting flag for RunModuleAgent. The value is either \sphinxstyleemphasis{True} or \sphinxstyleemphasis{False}.

\end{itemize}

\end{description}\end{quote}

\subsection{AgentTools.GenericModelAgent.ForcingDataFileGenerator module}
\label{\detokenize{AgentTools.GenericModelAgent:module-AgentTools.GenericModelAgent.ForcingDataFileGenerator}}\label{\detokenize{AgentTools.GenericModelAgent:agenttools-genericmodelagent-forcingdatafilegenerator-module}}\index{AgentTools.GenericModelAgent.ForcingDataFileGenerator (module)@\spxentry{AgentTools.GenericModelAgent.ForcingDataFileGenerator}\spxextra{module}}\index{ForcingDataFileGenerator (class in AgentTools.GenericModelAgent.ForcingDataFileGenerator)@\spxentry{ForcingDataFileGenerator}\spxextra{class in AgentTools.GenericModelAgent.ForcingDataFileGenerator}}

\begin{fulllineitems}
\phantomsection\label{\detokenize{AgentTools.GenericModelAgent:AgentTools.GenericModelAgent.ForcingDataFileGenerator.ForcingDataFileGenerator}}\pysiglinewithargsret{\sphinxbfcode{\sphinxupquote{class }}\sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{AgentTools.GenericModelAgent.ForcingDataFileGenerator.}}\sphinxbfcode{\sphinxupquote{ForcingDataFileGenerator}}}{\emph{*args}, \emph{**kwargs}}{}
ForcingDataFileGenerator Organizes the forcing data brought by the MainGenerator. 
The user should be aware of the expected format of the forcing data for their model.
By default, this module creates forcing data in a folder names ‘Forcing’. Such forcing data is 
always created as timeseries where different columns hold different variables, ie:
\begin{quote}

\sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{(Precipitation\_t0 \textbar{} Temerature\_t0 \textbar{} Wind\_t0, etc)}}

\sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{(Precipitation\_t1 \textbar{} Temerature\_t1 \textbar{} Wind\_t1, etc)}}

\sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{(Precipitation\_t2 \textbar{} Temerature\_t2 \textbar{} Wind\_t2, etc)}}

\sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{(Precipitation\_t3 \textbar{} Temerature\_t3 \textbar{} Wind\_t3, etc)}}
\end{quote}

and the data is divided in different files, were each one represents a single cell of the forcing inputs. 
So, a 2 by 2 (2x2) model will generate 4 files, each one with the full timeseries of the forcing data.
\begin{quote}\begin{description}
\item[{Input Ports}] \leavevmode\begin{itemize}
\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{WD\_Path:} This is the working folder provided by the MainGenerator module.

\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{DataSet\_Class:} This is the dataset information provided by the MainGenerator module.

\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{Forcing\_Folder\_Name:} \sphinxstylestrong{{[}Optional{]}} Name of the subfolder where the forcing info will be stored. The default value is \sphinxstyleemphasis{Forcing}.

\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{Forcing\_File\_Prefix:} \sphinxstylestrong{{[}Optional{]}} Prefix for the name of the forcing files. The default value is \sphinxstyleemphasis{data}.

\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{Date\_Label\_Format:} \sphinxstylestrong{{[}Optional{]}} Format taken for the dates of the first column.(i.e 05/16/1997-05:30:00 can be expressed as \%m/\%d/\%YYYY-\%H:\%M:\%S ),         The default value is \sphinxtitleref{None}, which means the files will not have dates. For more information about python date formats go to \sphinxurl{https://strftime.org/}

\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{Subrange:} \sphinxstylestrong{{[}Optional{]}} Subset of the dataset by giving the boundary limitation including x\_min, x\_max, y\_min, y\_max.

\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{Mask\_File:} \sphinxstylestrong{{[}Optional{]}} Mask file for generating specific forcing data files, there are two types of mask files, which are inclusive and exclusive.        In the mask file, it records the latitude and longitude of the cell each line, and for inclusive mask file, the ForcingDataFileGenerator module will only        yield the forcing data files of the certain cell given in mask file. and in reverse, the exclusive mask file provided to create the forcing data files of the cells which is excluded in the mask file.        The format of the mask file, should be \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{latitude,longitude}} each line, and user can make comment freely in any other line.

\end{itemize}

\item[{Output Ports}] \leavevmode\begin{itemize}
\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{Ready:} Starting flag for RunModuleAgent. The value is either \sphinxstyleemphasis{True} or \sphinxstyleemphasis{False}.

\end{itemize}

\end{description}\end{quote}

\subsection{AgentTools.GenericModelAgent.MainGenerator module}
\label{\detokenize{AgentTools.GenericModelAgent:module-AgentTools.GenericModelAgent.MainGenerator}}\label{\detokenize{AgentTools.GenericModelAgent:agenttools-genericmodelagent-maingenerator-module}}\index{AgentTools.GenericModelAgent.MainGenerator (module)@\spxentry{AgentTools.GenericModelAgent.MainGenerator}\spxextra{module}}\index{MainGenerator (class in AgentTools.GenericModelAgent.MainGenerator)@\spxentry{MainGenerator}\spxextra{class in AgentTools.GenericModelAgent.MainGenerator}}

\begin{fulllineitems}
\phantomsection\label{\detokenize{AgentTools.GenericModelAgent:AgentTools.GenericModelAgent.MainGenerator.MainGenerator}}\pysiglinewithargsret{\sphinxbfcode{\sphinxupquote{class }}\sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{AgentTools.GenericModelAgent.MainGenerator.}}\sphinxbfcode{\sphinxupquote{MainGenerator}}}{\emph{*args}, \emph{**kwargs}}{}
The MainGenerator module is the first component of the Generic Model Agent tools.
This component is responsible for setting up the folder where the simulation will be performed.
It receives all the forcing datasets as inputs. The order at which they are added matters,
since the final forcing files will display the data in the same order:
first Dataset\_01, then Dataset\_02, and so on.
The purpose of the Generic Model Agent tools is to enable the integration of new Models into the
CyberWater environment. Therefore, users are expected to be highly knowledgeable about the
details of their own models if they want to perform an integration with the Generic tools.
\begin{quote}\begin{description}
\item[{Input Ports}] \leavevmode\begin{itemize}
\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{01\_Path:} Path of the folder where the files of the simulation will be created.

\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{02\_GPF:} Path of the main configuration (global parameter) file for the simulation.

\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{03\_Override?:} Flag on whether to override the original working directory, The value is either \sphinxstyleemphasis{True} or \sphinxstyleemphasis{False}.

\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{04\_Ready:} Ready signal from precedent-connected modules, The value is either \sphinxstyleemphasis{True} or \sphinxstyleemphasis{False},

\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{Dataset\_x:} Dataset of the x-th forcing variable, (x=01,02,03,…,15).

\end{itemize}

\item[{Output Ports}] \leavevmode\begin{itemize}
\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{WD\_Path:} Folder where the execution will be performed.

\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{DataSet\_Class:} The information of the forcing datasets.

\end{itemize}

\end{description}\end{quote}

\begin{fulllineitems}
\phantomsection\label{\detokenize{AgentTools.GenericModelAgent:AgentTools.GenericModelAgent.MainGenerator.MainGenerator.compute}}\pysiglinewithargsret{\sphinxbfcode{\sphinxupquote{compute}}}{}{}
The main function of MainGenerator module is to retrieve the inputs from GUI,         and  setup the folder where the simulation will be performed.        It receives all the forcing datasets and integrates them in an overall dataset as output.

\label{\detokenize{AgentTools.GenericModelAgent:module-AgentTools.GenericModelAgent.RunModuleAgent}}\label{\detokenize{AgentTools.GenericModelAgent:agenttools-genericmodelagent-runmoduleagent-module}}\index{AgentTools.GenericModelAgent.RunModuleAgent (module)@\spxentry{AgentTools.GenericModelAgent.RunModuleAgent}\spxextra{module}}\index{RunModuleAgent (class in AgentTools.GenericModelAgent.RunModuleAgent)@\spxentry{RunModuleAgent}\spxextra{class in AgentTools.GenericModelAgent.RunModuleAgent}}

\begin{fulllineitems}
\phantomsection\label{\detokenize{AgentTools.GenericModelAgent:AgentTools.GenericModelAgent.RunModuleAgent.RunModuleAgent}}\pysiglinewithargsret{\sphinxbfcode{\sphinxupquote{class }}\sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{AgentTools.GenericModelAgent.RunModuleAgent.}}\sphinxbfcode{\sphinxupquote{RunModuleAgent}}}{\emph{*args}, \emph{**kwargs}}{}
RunModuleAgent responsible for the execution of a Model offered as executable. 
The model execution requires that the user manually prepares the files required.
\begin{quote}\begin{description}
\item[{Input Ports}] \leavevmode\begin{quote}\begin{description}
\item[{01\_Output\_Name}] \leavevmode
The list of the name of the output dataset

\item[{02\_File\_Position}] \leavevmode
The list of the position (column index) in the result files (e.g. model results files) for the corresponding output dataset.

\item[{03\_Model\_executable}] \leavevmode\begin{itemize}
\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{exe:} executable file with the execution parameters excluding the arguments.

\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{arg:} arguments required for the execution.

\end{itemize}

\item[{04\_Results\_format}] \leavevmode\begin{itemize}
\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{Result\_File\_Prefix/Name:} Either the prefix of all the cells generated by the model. Or the name of the time-series generated.

\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{Result\_File\_Separator:} Separation character in the output files.

\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{Result\_Folder:} The name of the folder saving the result data. The default value is \sphinxstyleemphasis{results}

\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{Point\_output?:} Check if the output is a single time-series in contrast of a distributed result in multiple files, once per cell.  The defalut value is \sphinxstyleemphasis{False}.

\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{Header\_lines:} Number of lines at the top of the resulting files that need to be ignored.

\end{itemize}

\item[{05\_Final\_state\_options {[}Optional{]}}] \leavevmode\begin{itemize}
\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{final\_state\_name:} The name of the final state file.

\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{save\_path:} The saving path of the final state file.

\end{itemize}

\item[{Ready\_List}] \leavevmode
Connect the output of ForcingDataFileGenerator, AreaWiseParamGenerator and InitialStateFileGenerator if it exists.

\item[{WD\_Path}] \leavevmode
WD\_Path output port of the MainGenerator. This is the directory where the simulation files are saved.

\item[{DataSet\_Class}] \leavevmode
DataSet\_Class output port of the MainGenerator.

\end{description}\end{quote}

\item[{Output Ports}] \leavevmode\begin{itemize}
\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{Outputx:}  Output dataset x. (x=01,02,03,….,20)

\end{itemize}

\end{description}\end{quote}

\subsection{AgentTools.HPC.HPC module}
\label{\detokenize{AgentTools.HPC:module-AgentTools.HPC.HPC}}\label{\detokenize{AgentTools.HPC:agenttools-hpc-hpc-module}}\index{AgentTools.HPC.HPC (module)@\spxentry{AgentTools.HPC.HPC}\spxextra{module}}\index{HPC (class in AgentTools.HPC.HPC)@\spxentry{HPC}\spxextra{class in AgentTools.HPC.HPC}}

\begin{fulllineitems}
\phantomsection\label{\detokenize{AgentTools.HPC:AgentTools.HPC.HPC.HPC}}\pysiglinewithargsret{\sphinxbfcode{\sphinxupquote{class }}\sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{AgentTools.HPC.HPC.}}\sphinxbfcode{\sphinxupquote{HPC}}}{\emph{*args}, \emph{**kwargs}}{}
HPC module is responsible for the execution of a Model on a remote high-performance computing platform.
\begin{quote}\begin{description}
\item[{Input Ports}] \leavevmode\begin{quote}\begin{description}
\item[{(1) Platform Selection}] \leavevmode\begin{itemize}
\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{SSH Platform:} Platform for SSH connection, including 6 slurm-based platforms: bigred3, bridges2, bridges2-shared, stampede2, google cloud, and jetstream, and 4 bash-based platforms: sievert, rain, thunder, and lightning.

\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{Gateway Platform:} Platform for gateway connection, including bigred3, bridges2, bridges2-shared and carbonate.

\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{Customized:} Customized based-based platform for user to connect, user can choose to save their customized platform, so that this server option will be displayed in the list of SSH Platform next time.

\end{itemize}

\item[{(2) Credential}] \leavevmode\begin{itemize}
\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{Username:} Username for high performance computing platform.

\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{Password:} Password for high performance computing platform.

\end{itemize}

\item[{(3) Project Configuration}] \leavevmode\begin{itemize}
\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{Project Name:} The name of project created in high-performance computing platform.

\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{Email:} User will receive a notification email when job done.

\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{Estimated Runtime:} The duration of the task in the platform which user want to apply for, and the default value is 5 minus.

\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{Argument:} Argument required for the model execution. e.g., -g vic\_global\_file\_val

\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{Result File Prefix:} The prefix of all the cells generated by the model.

\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{Point Output:}  (True/False). Check if the output is a single time-series in contrast of a distributed result in multiple files, once per cell. Default = False.

\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{Result File Separator:}  Separation character in the output files. Default = ‘ ‘

\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{Header Lines:}  Number of lines at the top of the resulting files that need to be ignored. Default = 0

\end{itemize}

\item[{(4) Model Source}] \leavevmode\begin{itemize}
\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{Executable Program:} The file path of the executable program of computation model, e.g., vicNl.exe.

\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{Source Code:} The directory path of the source code of computation model,             if there is no available executable program running in the high-performance computing platform.            The output executable name set in MakeFile should be same as the folder name of source code, e.g., vicNl

\end{itemize}

\item[{(5) Output Datasets}] \leavevmode\begin{itemize}
\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{Output Name:} Name of the output dataset x. (x=01,02,03,….,20)

\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{File Pos:} Column index in the result files for the dataset x. (x=01,02,03,….,20)

\end{itemize}

\item[{Ready\_List}] \leavevmode
Connect the output of ForcingDataFileGenerator, AreaWiseParamGenerator and InitialStateFileGenerator if it exists.

\item[{WD\_Path}] \leavevmode
WD\_Path output port of the MainGenerator. This is the directory where the simulation files are saved.

\item[{DataSet\_Class}] \leavevmode
DataSet\_Class output port of the MainGenerator.

\end{description}\end{quote}

\item[{Output Ports}] \leavevmode\begin{itemize}
\item {} 
\sphinxstylestrong{Outputx:}  Output dataset x. (x=01,02,03,….,20)

\end{itemize}

\end{description}\end{quote}

\index{search\_file\_with\_closest\_lat\_lon() (AgentTools.util.OutputUtil.OutputUtil static method)@\spxentry{search\_file\_with\_closest\_lat\_lon()}\spxextra{AgentTools.util.OutputUtil.OutputUtil static method}}

\begin{fulllineitems}
\phantomsection\label{\detokenize{AgentTools.util:AgentTools.util.OutputUtil.OutputUtil.search_file_with_closest_lat_lon}}\pysiglinewithargsret{\sphinxbfcode{\sphinxupquote{static }}\sphinxbfcode{\sphinxupquote{search\_file\_with\_closest\_lat\_lon}}}{\emph{estimated\_lat}, \emph{estimated\_lon}, \emph{directory}, \emph{filename\_pattern}, \emph{min\_resolution}}{}
This function takes an estimation of a latitude and longitude coordinates of a specific cell (in a distributed
output scenario), together with a directory where a list of cells are saved, and returns the name of the file
with the closest coordinates to the given ones. If the resulting coordinate gives a difference superior to the
current resolution, it throws an error.
